ertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 315<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/10/03 6:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=449.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Kalashnikovs and freedom</span><hr size=1> If people are law-abiding and have passed all the requirements, what's the problem? An AR-15 is the copy of what our guys used in 'Nam, and has a venerable history (sort of a love-hate relationship, actually). Maybe not as respectable as an M-1 or Springfield, but it carries value for some. I'd trust it, since it works well enough and I know it well from my service days. (I'd rather have an SR-25 though) Definitely could protect my home and neighbors with it, though maybe it could be argued that a pistol is more apt, but why mandate that by law if nobody is being hurt by my eccentricity?<br>
If I want to keep up with my skills, and use it maybe for hunting, Why not?<br>
<br>
It holds value to them, and they're law abiding. That should be enough. Actually, it's not for me to show why they should be allowed to keep these types of arms -it's for the detractors to show beyond any doubt that nobody should be able to own them.<br>
<br>
Remember the case in L.A a few years ago, where a couple of guys made custom kevlar armor to rob banks? The police on the scene couldn't stop them with their regular carry weapons and the SWAT guys were held up in traffic for over 30 minutes. A gun store owner donated what the media would call &quot;assault weapons&quot;.<br>
That points up another: bad guys won't be stopped by the laws. If defense is a viable cause for ownership, then why not the capability for more than a shotgun or pistol?<br>
 We're already stipulating knowledgeable, lawful people.<br>
Are you honestly suggesting that anybody who might have an interest in a possibly collectible, authentic piece of history should be considered dangerous?<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;Since police started keeping statistics, we now know that assault weapons are/were used in an underwhelming 0.026 of 1% of crimes in New Jersey. This means that my officers are more likely to encounter an escaped tiger from the zoo than to confront an assault weapon in the hands of of a drug-crazed killer on the streets....&quot;    Joseph Constance, Deputy Police Chief, Trenton, NJ<br>
<br>
&quot;I've never encountered an assault rifle.&quot;  Dominick Polifrone, Chief of New Jersey BATF: The New York Times, June 20, 1993<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
